Yes, that works‚Äîbut you can shorten it.

map(attribute='value') yields a generator.

unique returns a list.

So these are equivalent in Ansible 2.9:

‚úÖ Recommended (explicitly materialize first):
... | map(attribute='value') | list | unique

‚úÖ Also fine (unique will materialize it):
... | map(attribute='value') | unique

üö´ Redundant:
... | map(attribute='value') | unique | list ‚Üê the last | list isn‚Äôt needed since unique already outputs a list.

I‚Äôd stick with | list | unique for clarity and consistency across filters.

